    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>LinkedIn Document Post</strong> is a post format that lets you upload a multi-page PDF and display it as a swipeable carousel directly inside the LinkedIn feed. Viewers scroll through slides without leaving the platform. The format consistently generates <strong>3x more saves and shares</strong> than standard image or text posts because each swipe registers as dwell time — the signal LinkedIn's algorithm weights most heavily for distribution.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Format type</div>
            <div class="tms-value">PDF Carousel</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Reach vs text post</div>
            <div class="tms-value">2-3x higher</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">If you're posting on LinkedIn and not using document posts, you're leaving the highest-reach format on the table. The mechanism is simple: people swipe, LinkedIn counts each swipe as engagement, and the algorithm distributes the post further in response.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a LinkedIn Document Post?</h2>
        <p>A LinkedIn Document Post is a specific post type you create by clicking the document icon (or "Share document") in the post composer. You upload a PDF, PowerPoint, Word doc, or similar file. LinkedIn converts it into a paginated carousel that renders inline in the feed on both mobile and desktop.</p>
        <p>Three things make Document Posts structurally different from other LinkedIn post types:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Native in-feed consumption.</strong> Viewers don't click out to a PDF viewer or external link. They swipe through slides inside the LinkedIn feed. Zero friction to content consumption.</li>
          <li><strong>Dwell time accumulation.</strong> Each swipe action keeps the viewer on the post. A 15-slide document where someone reads all 15 slides generates 15x the dwell time of a single-image post they scroll past in 1 second.</li>
          <li><strong>Downloadable as a lead asset.</strong> Viewers can download the original PDF. High-value documents (reports, templates, checklists) get downloaded and shared outside LinkedIn, extending reach beyond the feed.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why dwell time drives reach on LinkedIn</div>
          <p>LinkedIn's feed algorithm uses "viral actions" (likes, comments, shares) plus <strong>dwell time</strong> as distribution signals. A document post someone swipes through for 90 seconds registers far stronger than a text post someone reads in 5 seconds — even if both get the same number of likes. This is why document posts consistently outperform on reach.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why LinkedIn Document Posts matter for content strategy</h2>
        <p>The reach advantage is real, but Document Posts have four strategic benefits beyond raw impressions:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Content repurposing efficiency.</strong> One well-made PDF becomes a LinkedIn Document Post, a SlideShare upload, a downloadable lead magnet on your website, and a source for 10-15 single-slide images. The creation cost is spread across multiple distribution channels.</li>
          <li><strong>Trust-building at scale.</strong> A 15-slide breakdown of an industry trend, a case study with real numbers, or a step-by-step process positions you as a practitioner — not just a commentator. Document posts create the "I learned something here" moment that followers remember.</li>
          <li><strong>Search discoverability inside LinkedIn.</strong> LinkedIn's internal search surfaces document posts for relevant queries. A document titled "B2B LinkedIn Strategy Checklist 2026" appears in LinkedIn search results for people looking for that content.</li>
          <li><strong>Save rate is a compounding signal.</strong> When someone saves your document post, LinkedIn's algorithm treats it as a strong quality signal and continues distributing the post for days after initial publication. High save rates extend the active lifespan of a document post well beyond the typical 24-48 hour feed window.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How to create a LinkedIn Document Post</h2>
        <p>The process is straightforward. The strategy inside the document is where the work lives.</p>

        <ol>
          <li>Click "Start a post" on your LinkedIn feed.</li>
          <li>Click the document icon (it looks like a page with a folded corner) in the post composer toolbar.</li>
          <li>Upload your PDF or presentation file (max 100 MB, up to 300 pages).</li>
          <li>Add a title for the document — this appears as the carousel header in the feed.</li>
          <li>Write your post caption. The first 2-3 lines appear before the "See more" cutoff — make them count.</li>
          <li>Post. The PDF renders as a swipeable carousel immediately.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Document post anatomy</span><br>
          [Caption — first 2-3 lines visible] → hooks the scroll<br>
          [Slide 1] → <span class="uf-new">the promise (what they'll learn)</span><br>
          [Slides 2-14] → <span class="uf-new">the content (one idea per slide)</span><br>
          [Slide 15] → <span class="uf-new">CTA (follow / comment / DM / download)</span><br>
          [Document title] → <span class="uf-new">shows in search results</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="types">LinkedIn Document Post vs other LinkedIn content formats</h2>

