        <h2 id="examples">Real LinkedIn Document Post examples</h2>

        <h3>B2B consultant: from 200 to 2,000+ views per post</h3>
        <p>A B2B consultant shifted from text-only posts to document posts built around client frameworks. Posting a 12-slide "how we structured our outbound sequence" document generated 2,400 impressions on a profile with 1,800 followers — a 133% over-delivery rate. The key: each slide contained one specific, actionable idea that readers saved and referenced later.</p>

        <h3>DTC brand: 3x saves and shares</h3>
        <p>A direct-to-consumer skincare brand tested document posts against standard image posts over 30 days. Document posts generated 3x more saves and shares than their best-performing image post. The format they used: "10 ingredients to check before buying any moisturizer" — educational, specific, and genuinely useful to their target audience.</p>

        <h3>Recruiting agency: inbound applications tripled</h3>
        <p>A recruiting agency posted monthly "salary benchmarks by role" documents — each a 15-slide PDF with real compensation data by city and experience level. The documents spread beyond LinkedIn as candidates downloaded and shared them. Result: inbound applications tripled over 6 months without any increase in ad spend.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">LinkedIn Document Post vs LinkedIn Article — which to use</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use a Document Post when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You want maximum feed reach and impressions</li>
              <li>The content is visual or slide-based</li>
              <li>You want people to save and share the asset</li>
              <li>The content has a clear "one thing per slide" structure</li>
              <li>You're building a content library, not a single long read</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use a LinkedIn Article when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You want Google to index the content for SEO</li>
              <li>The content is long-form and requires headers and links</li>
              <li>You want the content to live at a permanent URL</li>
              <li>The topic requires detailed citations or references</li>
              <li>You're publishing for newsletter subscribers</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for LinkedIn Document Posts</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Hook on slide 1.</strong> The first slide is your thumbnail in the feed preview. It must communicate the value proposition in 5 words or fewer. "10 cold email mistakes killing your reply rate" beats "Cold Email Tips."</li>
          <li><strong>One idea per slide.</strong> Dense slides lose readers. Each slide should contain a single, complete thought that makes sense on its own. Readers who save documents often return to specific slides later.</li>
          <li><strong>10-20 slides is the sweet spot.</strong> Under 8 feels thin. Over 25 loses most readers before slide 15. For most topics, 12-15 slides with generous white space hits the right depth-to-completion balance.</li>
          <li><strong>End with a specific CTA.</strong> "Follow me for more" is weak. "Comment with your biggest challenge and I'll DM you a resource" generates 3-5x more comments. Make the CTA as specific as the content.</li>
          <li><strong>Post caption earns the first swipe.</strong> Your first 2-3 lines of caption text must create enough curiosity to make someone swipe the document. Write the caption before you design the document — it forces clarity.</li>
          <li><strong>Consistent visual template.</strong> Build or buy a Canva template and reuse it. Consistent visual identity makes your document posts recognizable in the feed over time, and recognition = saves.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish Tuesday-Thursday between 8-10am.</strong> LinkedIn audience is most active during business hours. Document posts need immediate engagement in the first 2 hours to trigger wider distribution.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — designing for desktop only</div>
          <p>Over 60% of LinkedIn usage is on mobile. Document carousels on mobile show slides in portrait orientation. If you design slides in 16:9 landscape and pack them with text, mobile viewers can't read them without zooming. Design all document posts in 4:5 or 1:1 format with large fonts (minimum 24pt for body text) to ensure they're readable on any screen size.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common LinkedIn Document Post mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Too much text per slide</strong> — readers skim on mobile. One headline + 3 bullet points per slide is usually the ceiling.</li>
          <li><strong>No visual hierarchy</strong> — slides with equal-weight text everywhere train readers to stop reading. Use size and color to guide the eye.</li>
          <li><strong>Uploading a dense report as-is</strong> — a 40-page PDF written for reading won't work as a swipeable carousel. Rework it into slides with one takeaway each.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping the download value</strong> — documents people want to keep get downloaded and shared. Build for reuse, not one-time consumption.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring comments</strong> — commenting back within the first hour of posting dramatically extends algorithmic distribution. Set a reminder to engage with every comment in the first 60 minutes.</li>
          <li><strong>Posting once and moving on</strong> — a high-performing document post can be reposted 6-9 months later to a largely new audience. Track your best performers and recycle them with updated data or framing.</li>
        </ul>

